snippet.title: Kyocera Hydro Edge
snippet.description: Consider the Kyocera Hydro Edge if you're looking for a low-price splash proof phone, but skip it if its water resistance isn't a main priority for you.

snippet.title: 7-foot crab robot may be future of underwater exploration
snippet.description: Crabster CR200, designed to overcome mobility challenges in rough water, is also a frighteningly awesome-looking robot.

snippet.title: Dell, Toshiba, Lenovo tablets dip below $250 at Microsoft Store
snippet.description: Windows 8.1 tablets packing quad-core Intel chips are getting downright cheap, as Microsoft Store leads the way on pricing.

snippet.title: Take a dip with the 3G Kyocera Hydro Edge
snippet.description: The Kyocera Hydro Edge is a waterproof handset that features a 4-inch screen, Android 4.1, and a 5-megapixel camera.

snippet.title: Samsung still smartphone king despite market share dip
snippet.description: The Korean handset maker's second-quarter smartphone share slipped to 30 percent, but that still far outstripped the competition, according to research firm IDC.

snippet.title: Crab dinner inspires cancer-removing robot
snippet.description: Researchers in Singapore create a robot that can remove early-stage stomach cancer, and it's all thanks to a chili crab dinner.

snippet.title: Cell phone sales dip globally, Gartner says
snippet.description: Gartner's report says mobile phone sales last year declined for the first time since 2009, but Apple and Samsung snagged the most market share.

snippet.title: Apple shares dip below $600, then bounce back
snippet.description: Concerns about Apple's threatened profit margins appear to be weighing on the stock, despite the company's upbeat talk in its conference call.

snippet.title: Take a dip with Boost's Kyocera Hydro (pictures)
snippet.description: Boost Mobile's Kyocera Hydro didn't stop ticking after taking a dive in the pool, and it runs on Android 4.0 Ice Cream Sandwich.

snippet.title: HP, Acer ultrabook prices dip to $648, $699
snippet.description: Acer and Hewlett-Packard are getting aggressive on ultrabook pricing. Acer has taken its lower-end model below $650.
